english:
  title: Inscription for the Tomb of Jeon Baekheun
  author: Choi Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    During the Dade era of the Yuan dynasty, when Heaven's mandate shone bright above and the four seas rested in peace, the Grand Commandant, the Loyal and Fierce King, ruled the Eastern lands for thirty-five years through the weight of hereditary merit and imperial kinship. In those days, scholars cultivated loyalty and integrity without needing exhortation; those who served in the Chinese court need not be mentioned, but even those who came to serve our kingdom were all circumspect and mindful, ashamed to engage in frivolity or deceit. Yet within the last twenty or thirty years, the customs of the world have crumbled day by day, with no dike to hold back the tide. Occasionally, when someone mentions the affairs of that former time, none fail to mock and point fingers, deeming them hopelessly antiquated. Though exemplars of the old order still remained, lately they have passed away one after another, and the refined spirit of those times has vanished entirely. Alas, how can one not lament this?

    The late Prime Counselor Jeon was a man who served the former king. He was a cautious and noble gentleman, named Shin, with the courtesy name Ip. His ancestors were registered in Cheonan, and his great-grandfather was the Minister of the Imperial Stables, Sejo; his grandfather was the Palace Usher Inryang, posthumously styled Minister of Personnel; and his father was the Privy Councillor Seung—all men of distinction. His mother, Lady Choi, was the granddaughter of the Grand Councillor Munjeong, enfeoffed as the Lady of Jie'an.

    Jeon first entered office through his father's rank. In the year Sinhchuk of the Dade era, as an attendant of the inner court, he sat for the civil examination and passed. The following year he was appointed Administrator of Sunggyeong. He then participated in the Political Affairs Office and was transferred to become Compiler of the Secret Archives. In the year Gapchin he was appointed Lecturer at the National Academy and received robes of gold and purple. In the year Jeongmi he went out as Vice-Administrator of Andong. In the year Giyu of the Zhida era he was summoned as Vice-Minister of Ceremonies and promoted to Grand Commandant of Sacrificial Rites. After three further transfers, he became Chief Courier. In the year Sinhae he went out as Governor of Gimhae, and in the following year was transferred to Seong'an. Two years later he moved to Suwon. In the year Gabin of the延祐 era, he was recalled as Censor-in-Chief and transferred to become Counselor of the Remonstrance Office and Personnel Bureau. In the year Jeongsa he was appointed Keeper of the Precious Texts Pavilion and concurrently held numerous other positions. In the year Gimi he went out as Governor of Gyerim, and in the year Sinyu was transferred to be Commander of Bokju. In the year Gajja of the Taiding era he was dismissed. In the year Gyeongo of the Zhishun era he was recalled and appointed Grand Inspector with rank of Upper Military Commander. The following year his post at the Remonstrance Office was terminated, and he became Joint Commissioner of the Privy Council. In the year Sinsin he was again dismissed and lived in retirement for eight years before passing away in the seventh month of the seventh day of the year Gimyo of the Later Yuan era, at the age of sixty-four.

    His first wife, Lady Lee, was enfeoffed as Lady of Sangdang and was the daughter of the Director of the Census. She predeceased him. He later married Lady Kim, enfeoffed as Lady of Hamchang, daughter of the Grand Protector of the Divine Tiger Guard. His sons were Seong'an, who became Administrator of the Court Ceremonial Office; the next became a Buddhist monk named Huichan of the Jogye order; and the youngest, Bulno, never entered office. His daughters married the former Director of the Imperial Genealogy Han Daesun and Li Chung-in, administrator of the Central Secretariat, with another younger daughter and a single grandson still in youth.

    Jeon's father held the rank of Privy Councillor in the court of the former king, serving in intimate positions and overseeing the assessment of officials. People praised his fairness, and when Jeon succeeded to these duties, he too was esteemed for following in his father's footsteps. When the king grew weary of direct governance, Jeon went out to administer a province. Though he subsequently held many offices and rose to high position, his greatest achievements lay in his external service, and the people mourned his departure even more deeply. Finally, as head of the Remonstrance Office, he exposed several corrupt aged officials and restrained servants who had usurped power, preventing them from burning the records of their former posts to escape accountability, thus reviving enfeebled standards—yet he was dismissed within a year. In all his duties, Jeon exerted his utmost while treating matters with stern gravity, so that petitions could not sway him. Though his household was poor, he gave no thought to accumulating wealth. Alas, this is what it means to be a true gentleman. In his later years, he took the name Baekheun—the cypress that does not wither even after winter's frost—embodying this spirit. He maintained profound friendship with the three masters Yija, Jukheon, and Ikjae, and they never deemed me foolish or base, but drew me into their company, allowing me to share in their refined conversation. Seong'an and the others have chosen the twenty-eighth day of the eighth month to relocate his coffin for burial in the rear valley behind Seonheung Temple east of the capital, a few paces south of the tomb of his first wife, Lady Lee. They have entrusted me with this inscription. How could I dare refuse?

    The inscription reads:

    Ah, why should I conceal my words?
    At times they serve to honor the dead,
    Inscribed in stone along the grave's dark path.
    To honor his memory, I write,
    yet shame accompanies every phrase.

    When I consider his life,
    he was ashamed to tread paths of injustice.
    But limited am I in talent,
    fearing my brush cannot capture his virtue.

    In the yellow springs, that distant realm,
    may he see me not as I am flawed,
    but as I strive to honor his name.
  footnotes:
    - The Dade era (大德, 1297-1307) refers to the reign of the Yuan emperor Temür Khan during the height of Yuan power in East Asia.
    - Chong Yeol (충렬왕), known as the Loyal and Fierce King, was the father of Korean crown prince Jeon, who brought the Goryeo kingdom under Yuan dominance.
    - Baekheun (柏軒) means 'Cypress Pavilion.' The cypress is a symbol in Chinese and Korean poetry of integrity and steadfastness, particularly because it does not lose its needles in winter.
    - The inscription itself is written in the classical manner, with the poet expressing humility about his own ability to capture the deceased's virtue through mere words.
